  <title>
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">Monthly Emergency Food Assistance</narrative>
  </title>
  <description type="2">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">With this project, WFP is aiming to procure and distribute family food rations enough to cover the food needs of 90,000 people (45,990 women and 44,010 men) under the general food assistance (GFA) programme over a period of six months. For this allocation, WFP is proposing to use this funding for Ar-Raqqa sub-district of Ar-Raqqa governorate, identified as one of the areas with the highest severity of needs by the Humanitarian Country Team (HCT), WFP&#x2019;s 2019 national Food Security Assessment/Food Security and Livelihoods Assessment (FSA/FSLA) and the Food Security Sector (FSS). 

As per WFP assessments, 69 percent of the total population in Ar-Raqqa subdistrict are food insecure, making it the subdistrict with the highest food needs in the governorate.  Furthermore, as per WFP&#x2019;s Vulnerability Analysis and Mapping (VAM), Ar-Raqqa is one of the governorates with the highest increase in the price of the standard food basket (up 229 percent year-on-year), which is further affecting the existing food insecurity in the area. Ar-Raqqa governorate also concentrates some of the highest food insecurity prevalence both in terms of moderate and severe food insecurity according the to WFP&#x2019;s 2019 national household-level Food Security Assessment (FSA) and Food Security and Livelihood Assessment (FSLA). The 2019 SMART survey results showed that Ar-Raqqa governorate ranks among the highest in terms of micronutrient deficiencies, with anaemia prevalence affecting 50% of women in child bearing age and 42 percent of children under 5 years of age. These statistics go to show that sustained food insecurity over time is affecting the dietary diversity and health conditions of vulnerable population groups.</narrative>
  </description>
